conversations.value:
Storing raw or weakly-hashed passwords makes offline cracking and account takeover trivial when your database is leaked. You must use a modern, memory-hard algorithm like Argon2 with safe parameters and constant-time verification.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;

// Very naive in-memory "user store"
struct UserStore {
    users: HashMap<String, String>, // username -> password (PLAINTEXT)
}

impl UserStore {
    fn new() -> Self {
        Self { users: HashMap::new() }
    }

    // Stores password in plaintext (vulnerable)
    fn register(&mut self, username: &str, password: &str) {
        self.users.insert(username.to_string(), password.to_string());
    }

    // Compares passwords directly (vulnerable)
    fn login(&self, username: &str, password: &str) -> bool {
        if let Some(stored) = self.users.get(username) {
            // Simple string equality (leaks timing & uses plaintext)
            stored == password
        } else {
            false
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let mut store = UserStore::new();

    // Attacker can later dump these passwords directly if DB leaks
    store.register("alice", "P@ssw0rd1");

    let ok = store.login("alice", "P@ssw0rd1");
    println!("Login success: {}", ok);
}
```

**Attack Payload** (offline attack after DB leak):
```bash
# Attacker exports stolen credentials to a file `creds.txt` like:
# alice:P@ssw0rd1
# bob:qwerty123

# Then uses tools or script to automatically try these passwords
# against many of the victim's other accounts (password reuse attack).

# Example pseudo-command using a password spraying tool
spray-credentials --user-list users.txt --pass-list extracted-passwords.txt --target https://bank.example.com
```

This scenario becomes much worse if passwords are hashed with fast algorithms like MD5/SHA-1/SHA-256 without salt; GPUs can crack billions of guesses per second using tools like hashcat.

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Passwords are stored in plaintext, so any DB compromise instantly reveals all user passwords.
- Even if sent over TLS, backend storage is still a single point of catastrophic failure.
- No salting, key stretching, or memory-hardness, enabling very fast offline cracking and credential stuffing across other services.

**SECURE VERSION**:

```rust
use argon2::{
    password_hash::{PasswordHash, PasswordHasher, PasswordVerifier, SaltString},
    Argon2,
};
use once_cell::sync::Lazy;
use rand_core::OsRng;
use subtle::ConstantTimeEq;
use std::collections::HashMap;

// Global Argon2 instance with safe, opinionated defaults
static ARGON2: Lazy<Argon2> = Lazy::new(|| Argon2::default());

struct UserStore {
    // username -> Argon2 PHC string (contains parameters + salt + hash)
    users: HashMap<String, String>,
}

impl UserStore {
    fn new() -> Self {
        Self { users: HashMap::new() }
    }

    fn register(&mut self, username: &str, password: &str) -> Result<(), String> {
        if password.len() < 12 {
            return Err("Password too short".into());
        }

        // Generate cryptographically secure random salt
        let salt = SaltString::generate(&mut OsRng);

        // Hash password with Argon2
        let password_hash = ARGON2
            .hash_password(password.as_bytes(), &salt)
            .map_err(|e| format!("Hashing error: {e}"))?
            .to_string();

        self.users.insert(username.to_string(), password_hash);
        Ok(())
    }

    fn login(&self, username: &str, password: &str) -> bool {
        // Always perform a verification-like operation to keep timing similar
        if let Some(stored_hash) = self.users.get(username) {
            match PasswordHash::new(stored_hash) {
                Ok(parsed_hash) => {
                    // Constant-time verification
                    ARGON2.verify_password(password.as_bytes(), &parsed_hash).is_ok()
                }
                Err(_) => false,
            }
        } else {
            // Fallback: fake verification to reduce username enumeration via timing
            let fake_hash = self.fake_hash();
            if let Ok(parsed_fake) = PasswordHash::new(&fake_hash) {
                let _ = ARGON2.verify_password(b"dummy", &parsed_fake);
            }
            false
        }
    }

    // Generate a one-time fake hash for nonexistent users
    fn fake_hash(&self) -> String {
        let salt = SaltString::generate(&mut OsRng);
        ARGON2
            .hash_password(b"dummy_password", &salt)
            .unwrap()
            .to_string()
    }
}

fn constant_time_equal(a: &str, b: &str) -> bool {
    a.as_bytes().ct_eq(b.as_bytes()).into()
}

fn main() -> Result<(), String> {
    let mut store = UserStore::new();

    store.register("alice", "Str0ng-Password!!")?;

    let ok = store.login("alice", "Str0ng-Password!!");
    println!("Login success: {}", ok);

    let bad = store.login("alice", "wrong-pass");
    println!("Login success: {}", bad);

    Ok(())
}
```

**Key Security Controls**:
- Argon2 password hashing with random salt: Each password is hashed with a unique salt and memory-hard algorithm, making precomputed tables useless and slowing offline cracking.
- Constant-time verification and fake work for missing users: Reduces timing side channels and username enumeration risks.
- Basic password policy & safe error handling: Enforces minimum complexity and returns generic errors without leaking internal details, while still propagating serious issues via `Result`.

In production, you need a consistent Argon2 configuration loaded from environment, centralized hashing/verification helpers, audit logging, and controls like rate limiting and lockout. You also want clear separation between authentication logic and transport (HTTP) layer.

**PRODUCTION PATTERN**:

```rust
use argon2::{
    password_hash::{PasswordHash, PasswordHasher, PasswordVerifier, SaltString},
    Algorithm, Argon2, Params, Version,
};
use axum::{
    extract::State,
    routing::post,
    Json, Router,
};
use once_cell::sync::Lazy;
use rand_core::OsRng;
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};
use std::{collections::HashMap, net::SocketAddr, sync::Arc};
use tokio::sync::Mutex;
use tracing::{error, info, warn};
use tracing_subscriber::EnvFilter;
use subtle::ConstantTimeEq;
use tower_http::trace::TraceLayer;

// --------- Argon2 Configuration (ENV-AWARE) ---------

#[derive(Clone)]
struct CryptoConfig {
    argon2: Argon2,
}

impl CryptoConfig {
    fn from_env() -> Self {
        // In production, load from env; here we hard-code safe-ish defaults.
        // Example production-level parameters (tune for your hardware):
        let mem_kib: u32 = std::env::var("ARGON2_MEMORY_KIB")
            .ok()
            .and_then(|v| v.parse().ok())
            .unwrap_or(64 * 1024); // 64 MiB
        let iterations: u32 = std::env::var("ARGON2_ITERATIONS")
            .ok()
            .and_then(|v| v.parse().ok())
            .unwrap_or(3);
        let parallelism: u32 = std::env::var("ARGON2_PARALLELISM")
            .ok()
            .and_then(|v| v.parse().ok())
            .unwrap_or(1);

        let params = Params::new(mem_kib, iterations, parallelism, None)
            .expect("Invalid Argon2 params");

        let argon2 = Argon2::new(Algorithm::Argon2id, Version::V0x13, params);

        Self { argon2 }
    }
}

// --------- Domain Types ---------

#[derive(Clone)]
struct AppState {
    users: Arc<Mutex<HashMap<String, String>>>, // username -> Argon2 PHC string
    crypto: CryptoConfig,
}

#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct RegisterRequest {
    username: String,
    password: String,
}

#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct LoginRequest {
    username: String,
    password: String,
}

#[derive(Serialize)]
struct ApiResponse {
    message: String,
}

// --------- Helper Functions ---------

async fn hash_password(crypto: &CryptoConfig, password: &str) -> Result<String, String> {
    if password.len() < 12 {
        return Err("Password too short".into());
    }

    let salt = SaltString::generate(&mut OsRng);

    crypto
        .argon2
        .hash_password(password.as_bytes(), &salt)
        .map_err(|e| format!("Hashing error: {e}"))
        .map(|ph| ph.to_string())
}

fn verify_password(crypto: &CryptoConfig, password: &str, hash: &str) -> bool {
    match PasswordHash::new(hash) {
        Ok(parsed) => crypto
            .argon2
            .verify_password(password.as_bytes(), &parsed)
            .is_ok(),
        Err(_) => false,
    }
}

fn constant_time_equal(a: &str, b: &str) -> bool {
    a.as_bytes().ct_eq(b.as_bytes()).into()
}

// --------- HTTP Handlers (with logging & basic protections) ---------

async fn register_handler(
    State(state): State<AppState>,
    Json(body): Json<RegisterRequest>,
) -> Json<ApiResponse> {
    // Basic username validation
    if body.username.len() < 3 || body.username.len() > 64 {
        warn!("registration_failed?user={} reason=invalid_username", body.username);
        return Json(ApiResponse {
            message: "Invalid username or password".into(),
        });
    }

    let hash = match hash_password(&state.crypto, &body.password).await {
        Ok(h) => h,
        Err(e) => {
            error!("password_hashing_error error={}", e);
            return Json(ApiResponse {
                message: "Internal error".into(),
            });
        }
    };

    let mut users = state.users.lock().await;
    if users.contains_key(&body.username) {
        warn!("registration_failed?user={} reason=already_exists", body.username);
        return Json(ApiResponse {
            message: "User already exists".into(),
        });
    }

    users.insert(body.username.clone(), hash);
    info!("user_registered user={}", body.username);

    Json(ApiResponse {
        message: "Registered".into(),
    })
}

async fn login_handler(
    State(state): State<AppState>,
    Json(body): Json<LoginRequest>,
) -> Json<ApiResponse> {
    // In real production, apply IP/user-based rate limiting and lockouts here.

    let users = state.users.lock().await;
    let maybe_hash = users.get(&body.username).cloned();
    drop(users);

    let success = if let Some(stored_hash) = maybe_hash {
        verify_password(&state.crypto, &body.password, &stored_hash)
    } else {
        // Fake verification for non-existent users to reduce enumeration
        let fake_hash = hash_password(&state.crypto, "DummyPassword123!")
            .await
            .unwrap_or_default();
        if fake_hash.is_empty() {
            false
        } else {
            verify_password(&state.crypto, "DummyPassword123!", &fake_hash)
        }
    };

    if success {
        info!("login_success user={}", body.username);
        Json(ApiResponse {
            message: "Login successful".into(),
        })
    } else {
        warn!("login_failed user={}", body.username);
        Json(ApiResponse {
            message: "Invalid credentials".into(),
        })
    }
}

// --------- Main (Server Setup, Logging, Basic Hardening) ---------

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    // Structured logging with environment-based level
    tracing_subscriber::fmt()
        .with_env_filter(EnvFilter::from_default_env())
        .init();

    let state = AppState {
        users: Arc::new(Mutex::new(HashMap::new())),
        crypto: CryptoConfig::from_env(),
    };

    let app = Router::new()
        .route("/register", post(register_handler))
        .route("/login", post(login_handler))
        .with_state(state)
        .layer(TraceLayer::new_for_http());

    // For a real web app, terminate TLS at a reverse proxy and enforce
    // security headers like Strict-Transport-Security, etc.

    let addr = SocketAddr::from(([127, 0, 0, 1], 3000));
    info!("starting_server addr={}", addr);
    axum::Server::bind(&addr)
        .serve(app.into_make_service())
        .await
        .unwrap();
}
```

**Defense in Depth Layers**:
1. **Strong, tunable Argon2id configuration**:
   - Code example:
     ```rust
     let params = Params::new(mem_kib, iterations, parallelism, None)
         .expect("Invalid Argon2 params");
     let argon2 = Argon2::new(Algorithm::Argon2id, Version::V0x13, params);
     ```
   - Memory-hard, time-costly hashing raises the bar for offline cracking using stolen hashes.

2. **Application-layer protections (validation, fake verification, generic errors)**:
   - Code example:
     ```rust
     if body.username.len() < 3 || body.username.len() > 64 { /* ... */ }
     let success = if let Some(stored_hash) = maybe_hash {
         verify_password(&state.crypto, &body.password, &stored_hash)
     } else {
         // Fake verification
     };
     ```
   - Prevents easy username enumeration and enforces minimal credential quality.

3. **Operational controls (logging, environment-specific tuning, future rate limiting)**:
   - Code example:
     ```rust
     info!("login_success user={}", body.username);
     warn!("login_failed user={}", body.username);

     let mem_kib: u32 = std::env::var("ARGON2_MEMORY_KIB")
         .ok()
         .and_then(|v| v.parse().ok())
         .unwrap_or(64 * 1024);
     ```
   - Enables monitoring, anomaly detection, and safe tuning of Argon2 parameters per environment.

**Additional Protections**:
- Integrate **rate limiting and lockout** at the route level (e.g., via middleware) to stop brute-force attempts (per-IP and per-account limits).
- Use **secure transport and headers**: terminate TLS correctly, enforce HSTS, and set cookies as `Secure`, `HttpOnly`, and `SameSite=Strict` for any session tokens issued after login.
- Implement **audit trails & alerting**: forward auth logs to a SIEM, alert on spikes in failed logins or registration abuse, and routinely re-evaluate Argon2 parameters as hardware improves.

Relying on a naive session implementation is dangerous because stolen or guessed session IDs can give attackers full account access. You need secure, random session IDs, proper expiry, and flags like HttpOnly/Secure.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```rust
use actix_web::{web, App, HttpRequest, HttpResponse, HttpServer, Responder, cookie::Cookie};
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};

struct AppState {
    // user -> password (plaintext, bad but not focus here)
    users: HashMap<String, String>,
    // session_id -> username
    sessions: Mutex<HashMap<String, String>>,
}

async fn login(form: web::Form<HashMap<String, String>>, data: web::Data<Arc<AppState>>) -> impl Responder {
    let username = form.get("username").cloned().unwrap_or_default();
    let password = form.get("password").cloned().unwrap_or_default();

    // Trivial auth
    if data.users.get(&username) == Some(&password) {
        // VULNERABLE: predictable session ID based on username
        let session_id = format!("session-{}", username);

        // store session without expiry
        let mut sessions = data.sessions.lock().unwrap();
        sessions.insert(session_id.clone(), username.clone());

        // VULNERABLE: no Secure/HttpOnly/SameSite flags, long lifetime
        let cookie = Cookie::build("session_id", session_id)
            .path("/")
            .max_age(time::Duration::days(30))
            .finish();

        HttpResponse::Ok().cookie(cookie).body("Logged in")
    } else {
        HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Invalid credentials")
    }
}

async fn profile(req: HttpRequest, data: web::Data<Arc<AppState>>) -> impl Responder {
    // VULNERABLE: trust any session_id cookie blindly
    if let Some(cookie) = req.cookie("session_id") {
        let session_id = cookie.value().to_string();
        let sessions = data.sessions.lock().unwrap();
        if let Some(username) = sessions.get(&session_id) {
            return HttpResponse::Ok().body(format!("Hello, {}", username));
        }
    }

    HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Please log in")
}

#[actix_web::main]
async fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    let mut users = HashMap::new();
    users.insert("alice".to_string(), "password123".to_string());

    let state = Arc::new(AppState {
        users,
        sessions: Mutex::new(HashMap::new()),
    });

    HttpServer::new(move || {
        App::new()
            .app_data(web::Data::new(state.clone()))
            .route("/login", web::post().to(login))
            .route("/profile", web::get().to(profile))
    })
    .bind(("127.0.0.1", 8080))?
    .run()
    .await
}
```

**Attack Payload** (cookie manipulation):
```text
# Attacker sets their browser cookie or intercepts a victim's request and injects:
Cookie: session_id=session-alice
```

This works because `session-alice` is predictable (derived from the username). An attacker who knows `alice` is a valid username can simply forge this cookie to impersonate her.

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Session IDs are predictable (`session-<username>`), so they can be guessed and forged.
- No expiration or invalidation logic: once created, sessions live "forever" (or 30 days) in memory.
- Missing Secure and HttpOnly flags allows easier theft via network eavesdropping on HTTP or client-side script access.

**SECURE VERSION**:

```rust
use actix_web::{web, App, HttpRequest, HttpResponse, HttpServer, Responder, cookie::Cookie};
use rand::{distributions::Alphanumeric, Rng};
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
use std::time::{Duration, SystemTime};

struct Session {
    username: String,
    expires_at: SystemTime,
}

struct AppState {
    users: HashMap<String, String>, // demo only; use hashed passwords in real code
    // session_id -> Session
    sessions: Mutex<HashMap<String, Session>>,
}

fn generate_session_id() -> String {
    rand::thread_rng()
        .sample_iter(&Alphanumeric)
        .take(64)
        .map(char::from)
        .collect()
}

async fn login(form: web::Form<HashMap<String, String>>, data: web::Data<Arc<AppState>>) -> impl Responder {
    let username = form.get("username").cloned().unwrap_or_default();
    let password = form.get("password").cloned().unwrap_or_default();

    if data.users.get(&username) == Some(&password) {
        let session_id = generate_session_id();
        let expires_at = SystemTime::now() + Duration::from_secs(30 * 60); // 30 minutes

        let mut sessions = data.sessions.lock().unwrap();
        sessions.insert(
            session_id.clone(),
            Session { username: username.clone(), expires_at },
        );

        // SECURE: HttpOnly, Secure, short lifetime, SameSite=Lax
        let cookie = Cookie::build("session_id", session_id)
            .path("/")
            .http_only(true)
            .secure(true) // requires HTTPS in production
            .max_age(time::Duration::minutes(30))
            .same_site(actix_web::cookie::SameSite::Lax)
            .finish();

        HttpResponse::Ok().cookie(cookie).body("Logged in")
    } else {
        // Fail securely without hinting which field was wrong
        HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Invalid credentials")
    }
}

fn validate_session<'a>(session_id: &str, data: &'a AppState) -> Option<String> {
    let mut sessions = data.sessions.lock().unwrap();

    if let Some(session) = sessions.get(session_id) {
        if SystemTime::now() <= session.expires_at {
            return Some(session.username.clone());
        }
    }

    // Remove expired session proactively
    sessions.remove(session_id);
    None
}

async fn profile(req: HttpRequest, data: web::Data<Arc<AppState>>) -> impl Responder {
    let state = data.get_ref();

    if let Some(cookie) = req.cookie("session_id") {
        let session_id = cookie.value().to_string();
        if let Some(username) = validate_session(&session_id, state) {
            return HttpResponse::Ok().body(format!("Hello, {}", username));
        }
    }

    HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Please log in")
}

#[actix_web::main]
async fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    let mut users = HashMap::new();
    users.insert("alice".to_string(), "password123".to_string());

    let state = Arc::new(AppState {
        users,
        sessions: Mutex::new(HashMap::new()),
    });

    HttpServer::new(move || {
        App::new()
            .app_data(web::Data::new(state.clone()))
            .route("/login", web::post().to(login))
            .route("/profile", web::get().to(profile))
    })
    .bind(("127.0.0.1", 8080))?
    .run()
    .await
}
```

**Key Security Controls**:
- Strong, random session IDs: Uses 64-character alphanumeric tokens from a CSPRNG, making guessing or brute forcing infeasible.
- Session expiration and invalidation: Each session has an `expires_at` timestamp; expired sessions are rejected and removed.
- Secure cookie attributes: `HttpOnly`, `Secure`, `SameSite=Lax`, and a short `max_age` limit cookie exposure and reduce theft and CSRF risk.

In production, you should treat session management as a critical security boundary: use session rotation to prevent fixation, support logout and idle timeouts, add rate limiting for login, and log authentication events for monitoring and incident response.

**PRODUCTION PATTERN**:

```rust
use actix_web::{
    cookie::{Cookie, SameSite},
    dev::ServiceRequest,
    web, App, Error as ActixError, HttpMessage, HttpRequest, HttpResponse, HttpServer,
    Responder,
};
use futures_util::future::{ok, Ready};
use rand::{distributions::Alphanumeric, Rng};
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
use std::time::{Duration, SystemTime};

#[derive(Clone)]
struct Session {
    username: String,
    created_at: SystemTime,
    last_seen: SystemTime,
    expires_at: SystemTime,
}

#[derive(Clone)]
struct AppState {
    env: String,
    users: HashMap<String, String>,
    sessions: Mutex<HashMap<String, Session>>, // session_id -> Session
    login_attempts: Mutex<HashMap<String, (u32, SystemTime)>>, // ip -> (count, window_start)
}

fn generate_session_id() -> String {
    rand::thread_rng()
        .sample_iter(&Alphanumeric)
        .take(64)
        .map(char::from)
        .collect()
}

fn build_session_cookie(env: &str, session_id: String, ttl: Duration) -> Cookie<'static> {
    let mut cookie_builder = Cookie::build("session_id", session_id)
        .path("/")
        .http_only(true)
        .same_site(SameSite::Lax)
        .max_age(time::Duration::seconds(ttl.as_secs() as i64));

    if env == "production" {
        cookie_builder = cookie_builder.secure(true);
    }

    cookie_builder.finish()
}

fn rate_limit_login(state: &AppState, ip: &str) -> bool {
    let mut map = state.login_attempts.lock().unwrap();
    let now = SystemTime::now();
    let window = Duration::from_secs(60);
    let max_attempts = 5;

    let entry = map.entry(ip.to_string()).or_insert((0, now));
    let (ref mut count, ref mut start) = *entry;

    if now.duration_since(*start).unwrap_or(Duration::ZERO) > window {
        *count = 0;
        *start = now;
    }

    if *count >= max_attempts {
        return false;
    }

    *count += 1;
    true
}

async fn login(
    req: HttpRequest,
    form: web::Form<HashMap<String, String>>,
    data: web::Data<Arc<AppState>>,
) -> impl Responder {
    let state = data.get_ref();
    let ip = req
        .peer_addr()
        .map(|a| a.ip().to_string())
        .unwrap_or_else(|| "unknown".to_string());

    if !rate_limit_login(state, &ip) {
        eprintln!("[WARN] Rate limit exceeded for IP {}", ip);
        return HttpResponse::TooManyRequests().body("Too many login attempts");
    }

    let username = form.get("username").cloned().unwrap_or_default();
    let password = form.get("password").cloned().unwrap_or_default();

    if state.users.get(&username) == Some(&password) {
        let now = SystemTime::now();
        let ttl = Duration::from_secs(30 * 60); // 30 minutes absolute
        let session_id = generate_session_id();
        let session = Session {
            username: username.clone(),
            created_at: now,
            last_seen: now,
            expires_at: now + ttl,
        };

        {
            let mut sessions = state.sessions.lock().unwrap();
            sessions.insert(session_id.clone(), session);
        }

        // Log successful login
        println!("[INFO] User '{}' logged in from {}", username, ip);

        let cookie = build_session_cookie(&state.env, session_id, ttl);
        HttpResponse::Ok().cookie(cookie).body("Logged in")
    } else {
        eprintln!("[WARN] Failed login for '{}' from {}", username, ip);
        HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Invalid credentials")
    }
}

async fn logout(req: HttpRequest, data: web::Data<Arc<AppState>>) -> impl Responder {
    let state = data.get_ref();
    if let Some(cookie) = req.cookie("session_id") {
        let session_id = cookie.value().to_string();
        let mut sessions = state.sessions.lock().unwrap();
        if sessions.remove(&session_id).is_some() {
            println!("[INFO] Session {} logged out", session_id);
        }
    }

    // Invalidate cookie on client
    let expired_cookie = Cookie::build("session_id", "")
        .path("/")
        .http_only(true)
        .max_age(time::Duration::seconds(0))
        .finish();

    HttpResponse::Ok().cookie(expired_cookie).body("Logged out")
}

fn validate_and_touch_session(state: &AppState, session_id: &str) -> Option<String> {
    let mut sessions = state.sessions.lock().unwrap();
    let now = SystemTime::now();
    let idle_timeout = Duration::from_secs(15 * 60); // 15 minutes idle timeout

    if let Some(sess) = sessions.get_mut(session_id) {
        if now > sess.expires_at {
            sessions.remove(session_id);
            return None;
        }

        if now
            .duration_since(sess.last_seen)
            .unwrap_or(Duration::ZERO)
            > idle_timeout
        {
            sessions.remove(session_id);
            return None;
        }

        sess.last_seen = now;
        return Some(sess.username.clone());
    }

    None
}

async fn profile(req: HttpRequest, data: web::Data<Arc<AppState>>) -> impl Responder {
    let state = data.get_ref();
    if let Some(cookie) = req.cookie("session_id") {
        let session_id = cookie.value().to_string();
        if let Some(username) = validate_and_touch_session(state, &session_id) {
            return HttpResponse::Ok().body(format!("Hello, {}", username));
        }
    }

    HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Please log in")
}

// Simple middleware-like check for monitoring unauthorized access attempts
fn auth_monitor(req: ServiceRequest) -> Ready<Result<ServiceRequest, ActixError>> {
    if req.path().starts_with("/profile") && req.cookie("session_id").is_none() {
        eprintln!(
            "[WARN] Unauthorized profile access attempt from {:?}",
            req.peer_addr()
        );
    }
    ok(req)
}

#[actix_web::main]
async fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    let env = std::env::var("APP_ENV").unwrap_or_else(|_| "development".to_string());

    let mut users = HashMap::new();
    // In production, store password hashes and use a proper KDF
    users.insert("alice".to_string(), "password123".to_string());

    let state = Arc::new(AppState {
        env,
        users,
        sessions: Mutex::new(HashMap::new()),
        login_attempts: Mutex::new(HashMap::new()),
    });

    HttpServer::new(move || {
        App::new()
            .wrap_fn(|req, srv| {
                // basic monitoring wrapper
                auth_monitor(req).and_then(|req| srv.call(req))
            })
            .app_data(web::Data::new(state.clone()))
            .route("/login", web::post().to(login))
            .route("/logout", web::post().to(logout))
            .route("/profile", web::get().to(profile))
    })
    .bind(("127.0.0.1", 8080))?
    .run()
    .await
}
```

**Defense in Depth Layers**:
1. **Strong session lifecycle management**:
   - Absolute expiry and idle timeout in `validate_and_touch_session`:
   ```rust
   if now > sess.expires_at { sessions.remove(session_id); }
   if now.duration_since(sess.last_seen)? > idle_timeout { sessions.remove(session_id); }
   ```
   Ensures sessions die even if a user forgets to log out and prevents long-lived stolen sessions.

2. **Session rotation and logout support**:
   - New session ID issued on each login and old ones can be invalidated on logout:
   ```rust
   let session_id = generate_session_id();
   sessions.insert(session_id.clone(), session);
   // ...
   sessions.remove(&session_id); // in logout
   ```
   Limits impact of fixation and allows users to terminate hijacked sessions.

3. **Rate limiting and monitoring around authentication**:
   - Basic IP-based login rate limiting and logging of failed attempts:
   ```rust
   if !rate_limit_login(state, &ip) {
       eprintln!("[WARN] Rate limit exceeded for IP {}", ip);
       return HttpResponse::TooManyRequests().body("Too many login attempts");
   }
   ```
   - Middleware-style monitoring of unauthorized access:
   ```rust
   if req.path().starts_with("/profile") && req.cookie("session_id").is_none() {
       eprintln!("[WARN] Unauthorized profile access attempt from {:?}", req.peer_addr());
   }
   ```

**Additional Protections**:
- **Environment-specific configuration**: Only sets `Secure` flag for cookies in production, controlled via `APP_ENV`, while still allowing local development over HTTP.
- **Audit logging**: Logs successful logins, failed logins, logouts, and suspicious access attempts to support detection and forensic analysis.
- **Graceful degradation**: Rate-limited or unauthorized users receive generic, non-verbose error messages (`401`, `429`) without leaking internal details, preserving security while keeping behavior predictable for clients.

A common critical mistake is to "just make TLS work" by disabling certificate validation or using outdated cipher suites. That can completely break authentication security, even if you use strong passwords or tokens.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```rust
use actix_web::{post, web, App, HttpResponse, HttpServer, Responder};
use serde::Deserialize;
use reqwest::Client;

#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct LoginRequest {
    username: String,
    password: String,
}

#[post("/login")]
async fn login(form: web::Json<LoginRequest>) -> impl Responder {
    // VULNERABLE: HTTP client to call an internal auth service over TLS
    let client = Client::builder()
        // Dangerous: accept any certificate (including self-signed or forged)
        .danger_accept_invalid_certs(true)
        // Dangerous: ignore hostname mismatch (MITM with valid cert for other domain)
        .danger_accept_invalid_hostnames(true)
        .build()
        .unwrap();

    let res = client
        .post("https://auth.internal.local/verify")
        .json(&*form)
        .send()
        .await
        .unwrap();

    if res.status().is_success() {
        HttpResponse::Ok().body("Logged in")
    } else {
        HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Invalid credentials")
    }
}

#[actix_web::main]
async fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    HttpServer::new(|| App::new().service(login))
        // Also vulnerable: using plain HTTP in production reverse proxy setups
        .bind(("0.0.0.0", 8080))?
        .run()
        .await
}
```

**Attack Payload** (TLS interception / forged cert):
```bash
# On attacker machine in a position to MITM (e.g., compromised router)
# 1. Obtain or create a certificate for attacker.com (or any domain)
# 2. Run a transparent proxy that presents this cert to the victim service
mitmproxy --mode transparent --ssl-insecure
```

This attack works here because the Rust client accepts any certificate and hostname. The attacker can proxy `https://auth.internal.local/verify`, see credentials in clear, and even spoof successful responses.

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Breaks TLS authentication: `danger_accept_invalid_certs(true)` disables cert validation, so any cert is trusted.
- Allows hostname spoofing: `danger_accept_invalid_hostnames(true)` lets a cert for some other domain be used to impersonate your auth service.
- Enables credential theft and auth bypass: a MITM can read passwords, modify responses, or always return 200 OK, bypassing real authentication.

**SECURE VERSION**:

```rust
use actix_web::{post, web, App, HttpResponse, HttpServer, Responder};
use actix_web::http::StatusCode;
use serde::Deserialize;
use reqwest::{Client, ClientBuilder};
use std::sync::Arc;
use std::time::Duration;
use tracing::{error, info};

#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct LoginRequest {
    username: String,
    password: String,
}

fn build_secure_client(auth_host: &str) -> anyhow::Result<Client> {
    // PRIMARY DEFENSE: use system roots and strict hostname verification
    let client = ClientBuilder::new()
        .https_only(true)
        .connect_timeout(Duration::from_secs(5))
        .timeout(Duration::from_secs(10))
        .user_agent("secure-auth-service/1.0")
        // Do NOT call danger_accept_invalid_certs / hostnames
        // Use default TLS backend with OS trust store
        .build()?;

    // Optionally: we can sanity check the auth_host format (defense in depth)
    if !auth_host.ends_with(".internal.local") {
        anyhow::bail!("Invalid auth host configuration");
    }

    Ok(client)
}

struct AppState {
    http_client: Client,
    auth_base_url: String,
}

#[post("/login")]
async fn login(data: web::Data<Arc<AppState>>, form: web::Json<LoginRequest>) -> impl Responder {
    // Basic input sanity check (defense in depth, not main auth)
    if form.username.len() > 128 || form.password.len() > 128 {
        return HttpResponse::BadRequest().body("Invalid input");
    }

    let url = format!("{}/verify", data.auth_base_url);

    let res = match data
        .http_client
        .post(&url)
        .json(&*form)
        .send()
        .await
    {
        Ok(r) => r,
        Err(e) => {
            error!(error = %e, "auth backend request failed");
            return HttpResponse::build(StatusCode::SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE)
                .body("Authentication service unavailable");
        }
    };

    if res.status().is_success() {
        info!(user = %form.username, "successful login");
        // Here you would issue a session token / cookie with secure flags
        HttpResponse::Ok().body("Logged in")
    } else if res.status() == StatusCode::UNAUTHORIZED {
        info!(user = %form.username, "failed login");
        HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Invalid credentials")
    } else {
        error!(
            status = %res.status(),
            "unexpected status from auth backend"
        );
        HttpResponse::build(StatusCode::SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE)
            .body("Authentication error")
    }
}

#[actix_web::main]
async fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    tracing_subscriber::fmt::init();

    // In production this comes from environment / config management
    let auth_base_url = std::env::var("AUTH_BASE_URL")
        .unwrap_or_else(|_| "https://auth.internal.local".to_string());

    let client = build_secure_client(&auth_base_url)
        .expect("Failed to build secure HTTP client");

    let state = Arc::new(AppState {
        http_client: client,
        auth_base_url,
    });

    HttpServer::new(move || {
        App::new()
            .app_data(web::Data::new(Arc::clone(&state)))
            .service(login)
    })
    // Frontend should be behind a reverse proxy that terminates TLS
    .bind(("0.0.0.0", 8080))?
    .run()
    .await
}
```

**Key Security Controls**:
- Strict TLS verification: rely on the default `reqwest` configuration with system CA roots and hostname verification to ensure you only talk to the genuine auth server.
- Secure configuration management: the `AUTH_BASE_URL` is validated and not overridden programmatically with unsafe options, reducing misconfiguration risk.
- Robust error handling and logging: authentication service failures return generic errors to the client while logging details server-side for monitoring, preventing information leaks and aiding incident response.

In production you want strong defaults, explicit environment-specific configuration, and multiple guardrails so that debugging conveniences (like disabling cert checks) can’t sneak into prod. Mutual TLS (mTLS) adds another layer to authenticate services to each other.

**PRODUCTION PATTERN**:

```rust
use actix_web::{post, web, App, HttpResponse, HttpServer, Responder};
use actix_web::http::StatusCode;
use serde::Deserialize;
use reqwest::{Client, ClientBuilder};
use std::fs;
use std::sync::Arc;
use std::time::Duration;
use tracing::{error, info, warn};
use anyhow::Context;

#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct LoginRequest {
    username: String,
    password: String,
}

#[derive(Clone)]
struct TlsConfig {
    env: String,
    auth_base_url: String,
    ca_bundle_path: Option<String>,
    client_cert_path: Option<String>,
    client_key_path: Option<String>,
}

fn load_tls_config() -> anyhow::Result<TlsConfig> {
    let env = std::env::var("APP_ENV").unwrap_or_else(|_| "development".into());
    let auth_base_url = std::env::var("AUTH_BASE_URL")
        .unwrap_or_else(|_| "https://auth.internal.local".to_string());

    // In production, require explicit CA and client certs for mTLS
    let ca_bundle_path = std::env::var("AUTH_CA_BUNDLE").ok();
    let client_cert_path = std::env::var("AUTH_CLIENT_CERT").ok();
    let client_key_path = std::env::var("AUTH_CLIENT_KEY").ok();

    if env == "production" {
        if !auth_base_url.starts_with("https://") {
            anyhow::bail!("In production, AUTH_BASE_URL must use HTTPS");
        }
    }

    Ok(TlsConfig {
        env,
        auth_base_url,
        ca_bundle_path,
        client_cert_path,
        client_key_path,
    })
}

fn build_mtls_client(cfg: &TlsConfig) -> anyhow::Result<Client> {
    let mut builder = ClientBuilder::new()
        .https_only(true)
        .connect_timeout(Duration::from_secs(5))
        .timeout(Duration::from_secs(10))
        .user_agent("secure-auth-service/1.0")
        .pool_max_idle_per_host(8);

    // Defense in depth: pin to private CA if provided
    if let Some(ca_path) = &cfg.ca_bundle_path {
        let ca_bytes = fs::read(ca_path)
            .with_context(|| format!("Failed to read CA bundle at {}", ca_path))?;
        let ca_cert = reqwest::Certificate::from_pem(&ca_bytes)
            .context("Invalid CA bundle PEM")?;
        builder = builder.add_root_certificate(ca_cert);
    }

    // Mutual TLS: client cert + key for service-to-service auth
    if let (Some(cert_path), Some(key_path)) = (&cfg.client_cert_path, &cfg.client_key_path) {
        let cert_bytes = fs::read(cert_path)
            .with_context(|| format!("Failed to read client cert at {}", cert_path))?;
        let key_bytes = fs::read(key_path)
            .with_context(|| format!("Failed to read client key at {}", key_path))?;

        let id = reqwest::Identity::from_pkcs8_pem(&cert_bytes, &key_bytes)
            .context("Invalid client identity (PKCS#8)")?;
        builder = builder.identity(id);
    } else if cfg.env == "production" {
        // Fail-closed in production if mTLS is expected
        warn!("Production environment without client certs: mTLS disabled");
    }

    // NEVER call danger_accept_invalid_certs / hostnames
    let client = builder.build().context("Failed to build HTTP client")?;
    Ok(client)
}

struct AppState {
    http_client: Client,
    cfg: TlsConfig,
}

#[post("/login")]
async fn login(data: web::Data<Arc<AppState>>, form: web::Json<LoginRequest>) -> impl Responder {
    // Rate limiting would normally be done via middleware / external gateway.
    if form.username.len() > 128 || form.password.len() > 128 {
        return HttpResponse::BadRequest().body("Invalid input");
    }

    let url = format!("{}/verify", data.cfg.auth_base_url);

    let res = match data
        .http_client
        .post(&url)
        .json(&*form)
        .send()
        .await
    {
        Ok(r) => r,
        Err(e) => {
            error!(error = %e, "auth backend request failed");
            // Graceful degradation: don't expose internals
            return HttpResponse::build(StatusCode::SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE)
                .body("Authentication service unavailable");
        }
    };

    // Audit logging: only log usernames, never passwords or tokens
    if res.status().is_success() {
        info!(user = %form.username, "login_success");
        HttpResponse::Ok()
            .insert_header(("X-Content-Type-Options", "nosniff"))
            .insert_header(("X-Frame-Options", "DENY"))
            .insert_header(("X-XSS-Protection", "0"))
            .body("Logged in")
    } else if res.status() == StatusCode::UNAUTHORIZED {
        info!(user = %form.username, "login_failed");
        HttpResponse::Unauthorized()
            .insert_header(("X-Content-Type-Options", "nosniff"))
            .body("Invalid credentials")
    } else {
        error!(
            status = %res.status(),
            "unexpected status from auth backend"
        );
        HttpResponse::build(StatusCode::SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE)
            .insert_header(("X-Content-Type-Options", "nosniff"))
            .body("Authentication error")
    }
}

#[actix_web::main]
async fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    tracing_subscriber::fmt::init();

    let cfg = load_tls_config().expect("invalid TLS configuration");
    info!(env = %cfg.env, "starting service");

    let client = build_mtls_client(&cfg).expect("failed to create TLS client");

    let state = Arc::new(AppState { http_client: client, cfg });

    // Environment-specific server config
    let bind_addr = if state.cfg.env == "production" {
        "0.0.0.0:8443"
    } else {
        "127.0.0.1:8080"
    };

    // TLS termination for inbound connections is typically done by a reverse proxy
    HttpServer::new(move || {
        App::new()
            .app_data(web::Data::new(Arc::clone(&state)))
            .service(login)
    })
    .bind(bind_addr)?
    .run()
    .await
}
```

**Defense in Depth Layers**:
1. **Strict TLS + mTLS for service-to-service auth**:
   ```rust
   let id = reqwest::Identity::from_pkcs8_pem(&cert_bytes, &key_bytes)?;
   builder = builder.identity(id); // client cert proves service identity
   ```
   This ensures both sides authenticate each other, preventing rogue services from impersonating the auth backend.

2. **Environment-specific, fail-closed configuration**:
   ```rust
   if env == "production" {
       if !auth_base_url.starts_with("https://") {
           anyhow::bail!("In production, AUTH_BASE_URL must use HTTPS");
       }
   }
   ```
   Production refuses unsafe URLs, so a misconfigured `http://` endpoint can't silently downgrade security.

3. **Monitoring, audit logging, and graceful degradation**:
   ```rust
   error!(error = %e, "auth backend request failed");
   return HttpResponse::build(StatusCode::SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE)
       .body("Authentication service unavailable");
   ```
   Errors are logged for alerting and debugging, but clients only see generic messages, preventing information leakage while maintaining availability.

**Additional Protections**:
- **Rate limiting and lockout**: implement per-IP and per-account rate limits (e.g., via a gateway or middleware) to reduce credential stuffing and brute-force attacks on the login endpoint.
- **Security headers and secure cookies**: ensure session cookies are `Secure`, `HttpOnly`, and `SameSite=Strict`, and add headers like `Strict-Transport-Security` at the reverse proxy to enforce HTTPS.
- **Certificate lifecycle management and pinning**: automate rotation of server and client certificates, and for high-sensitivity services consider certificate pinning or private CA roots to reduce the impact of public CA compromise or mis-issuance.

Hard-coding API secrets or authentication keys directly in your Rust source is dangerous because they end up in your Git history, builds, and logs. An attacker who gets access to your repo or binary can often extract them.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```rust
use actix_web::{web, App, HttpRequest, HttpResponse, HttpServer, Responder};

// DANGEROUS: Hard-coded API key in source and committed to Git
const API_SECRET: &str = "super-secret-prod-key-123456";

async fn protected_endpoint(req: HttpRequest) -> impl Responder {
    let auth_header = req
        .headers()
        .get("X-API-Key")
        .and_then(|v| v.to_str().ok());

    match auth_header {
        Some(key) if key == API_SECRET => {
            HttpResponse::Ok().body("Sensitive data for authorized client")
        }
        _ => HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Invalid API key"),
    }
}

#[actix_web::main]
async fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    // DANGEROUS: logging the secret during startup
    println!("Starting server with API_SECRET={}", API_SECRET);

    HttpServer::new(|| {
        App::new().route("/protected", web::get().to(protected_endpoint))
    })
    .bind(("127.0.0.1", 8080))?
    .run()
    .await
}
```

**Attack Payload** (conceptual example – attacker using stolen key):
```bash
curl -H "X-API-Key: super-secret-prod-key-123456" \
  http://localhost:8080/protected
```

If the secret is leaked via source control, build artifacts, screenshots, or logs, an attacker can call your protected API exactly like this and be fully authenticated.

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Secrets are embedded in source control history where they are hard to fully remove and easy to scrape.
- Compiled binaries and debug logs can reveal hard-coded secrets via reverse engineering or log collection.
- Rotating or revoking secrets becomes difficult because you must rebuild and redeploy code to change them.

**SECURE VERSION**:

```rust
use actix_web::{web, App, HttpRequest, HttpResponse, HttpServer, Responder};
use std::env;
use std::sync::Arc;

/// Configuration holding runtime-loaded secrets.
#[derive(Clone)]
struct AppConfig {
    api_secret: Arc<String>,
}

async fn protected_endpoint(req: HttpRequest, cfg: web::Data<AppConfig>) -> impl Responder {
    let auth_header = req
        .headers()
        .get("X-API-Key")
        .and_then(|v| v.to_str().ok());

    match auth_header {
        Some(key) if constant_time_eq(key.as_bytes(), cfg.api_secret.as_bytes()) => {
            HttpResponse::Ok().body("Sensitive data for authorized client")
        }
        _ => HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Invalid API key"),
    }
}

/// Constant-time comparison to reduce timing side channels.
fn constant_time_eq(a: &[u8], b: &[u8]) -> bool {
    if a.len() != b.len() {
        return false;
    }
    let mut diff: u8 = 0;
    for i in 0..a.len() {
        diff |= a[i] ^ b[i];
    }
    diff == 0
}

#[actix_web::main]
async fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    // PRIMARY DEFENSE: Load secret from environment (or secret manager), not from code.
    let api_secret = match env::var("API_SECRET") {
        Ok(val) if !val.is_empty() => val,
        _ => {
            // Fail securely if secret is missing or empty.
            eprintln!("FATAL: API_SECRET environment variable is not set or empty");
            std::process::exit(1);
        }
    };

    let cfg = AppConfig {
        api_secret: Arc::new(api_secret),
    };

    HttpServer::new(move || {
        App::new()
            .app_data(web::Data::new(cfg.clone()))
            .route("/protected", web::get().to(protected_endpoint))
    })
    .bind(("127.0.0.1", 8080))?
    .run()
    .await
}
```

**Key Security Controls**:
- **External secret storage (environment/secret manager)**: Secrets are injected at runtime via environment variables or a dedicated secrets manager, keeping them out of source control and binary images.
- **Fail-secure startup**: The application refuses to start if the secret is missing or invalid, preventing accidental exposure of an unprotected API.
- **Constant-time comparison**: Uses a timing-attack-resistant comparison function to avoid leaking information about the secret's value through response timing differences.

In production, you typically need multiple active keys (for rotation), per-environment configuration, robust logging, and monitoring. You should load secrets from a secure store, support key IDs, and avoid breaking clients during rotation.

**PRODUCTION PATTERN**:

```rust
use actix_web::{web, App, HttpRequest, HttpResponse, HttpServer, Responder};
use chrono::Utc;
use serde::Deserialize;
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::env;
use std::sync::Arc;

#[derive(Clone, Debug, PartialEq, Eq)]
enum Environment {
    Dev,
    Staging,
    Prod,
}

#[derive(Clone)]
struct AppConfig {
    env: Environment,
    // Map of key_id -> secret, to support rotation
    api_keys: Arc<HashMap<String, String>>, // secrets kept in memory only
    // Active key id for generating new tokens, if applicable
    active_key_id: Arc<String>,
}

#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct ApiAuthHeader {
    // e.g., "key-2025-01:abcdef123" -> key_id and key_value
    #[serde(rename = "X-API-Key")]
    _ignored: String,
}

async fn protected_endpoint(req: HttpRequest, cfg: web::Data<AppConfig>) -> impl Responder {
    let remote_addr = req
        .peer_addr()
        .map(|a| a.to_string())
        .unwrap_or_else(|| "unknown".to_string());

    let auth_header = req
        .headers()
        .get("X-API-Key")
        .and_then(|v| v.to_str().ok());

    let (key_id, key_val) = match auth_header.and_then(parse_key_header) {
        Some(parts) => parts,
        None => {
            audit_log(
                &cfg,
                &remote_addr,
                "auth_failure",
                "missing_or_malformed_key",
            );
            return HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Unauthorized");
        }
    };

    match cfg.api_keys.get(&key_id) {
        Some(stored) if constant_time_eq(stored.as_bytes(), key_val.as_bytes()) => {
            audit_log(&cfg, &remote_addr, "auth_success", &key_id);
            HttpResponse::Ok().body("Sensitive data for authorized client")
        }
        _ => {
            audit_log(&cfg, &remote_addr, "auth_failure", "invalid_key");
            HttpResponse::Unauthorized().body("Unauthorized")
        }
    }
}

fn parse_key_header(header: &str) -> Option<(String, String)> {
    // Expect format: "<key_id>:<key_value>"
    let parts: Vec<&str> = header.splitn(2, ':').collect();
    if parts.len() != 2 || parts[0].is_empty() || parts[1].is_empty() {
        return None;
    }
    Some((parts[0].to_string(), parts[1].to_string()))
}

fn constant_time_eq(a: &[u8], b: &[u8]) -> bool {
    if a.len() != b.len() {
        return false;
    }
    let mut diff: u8 = 0;
    for i in 0..a.len() {
        diff |= a[i] ^ b[i];
    }
    diff == 0
}

fn load_env() -> Environment {
    match env::var("APP_ENV").unwrap_or_else(|_| "dev".to_string()).as_str() {
        "prod" => Environment::Prod,
        "staging" => Environment::Staging,
        _ => Environment::Dev,
    }
}

fn load_keys_from_env() -> (HashMap<String, String>, String) {
    // Example env variables:
    // API_KEYS="key-2024-12,old-key-2024-06"
    // API_KEY_key-2024-12="secret1"
    // API_KEY_old-key-2024-06="secret2"
    // ACTIVE_KEY_ID="key-2024-12"
    let key_ids = env::var("API_KEYS").unwrap_or_default();
    let mut map = HashMap::new();

    for key_id in key_ids.split(',').map(|s| s.trim()).filter(|s| !s.is_empty()) {
        let var_name = format!("API_KEY_{}", key_id);
        if let Ok(val) = env::var(&var_name) {
            if !val.is_empty() {
                map.insert(key_id.to_string(), val);
            }
        }
    }

    let active_id = env::var("ACTIVE_KEY_ID").unwrap_or_default();
    if active_id.is_empty() || !map.contains_key(&active_id) {
        eprintln!("FATAL: ACTIVE_KEY_ID is missing or not present in API_KEYS");
        std::process::exit(1);
    }

    if map.is_empty() {
        eprintln!("FATAL: No API keys loaded; check API_KEYS and API_KEY_* env vars");
        std::process::exit(1);
    }

    (map, active_id)
}

